LAGOS – The Nigeria Customs Service (NCS), Tincan Island Command, Apapa, Lagos, has disclosed how it intercepted and seized a number of illicit drugs, unwholesome goods and other contrabands at Tincan Island Port, Lagos. The command said the Duty Paid Value (DPV), of the seized items, is N1,048,810,569.00. Comptroller Adekunle Oloyede, Customs Area Controller of the Command disclosed this during a press briefing in Lagos. The intercepted items, according to the Customs boss, include 145kg of Colorado otherwise known as Indian Hemp, which was concealed in two units of Ridgeline trucks and two units of Toyota Corolla vehicles; 206,000 pieces of machetes; 640 bales of used clothes; 236,500 pieces of used shoes; 62,500 pieces of new lady’s shoes; 1,670,400 pieces of Chlorine injections (5mg/5ml);1,814,400 pieces of Novalgen injection (500mg/5ml); 48,850 rolls of cigarettes and 23,800 tins of sodium bromide and baking powder. Comptroller Oloyede said: “The importation of these products contravenes Sections 46, 47 and 161 of the Customs and Excise Management Act (CEMA), Cap 45 LFN, 2004. He also said that in line with trade facilitation, through export, traders exported 71,014.4 metric tonnes of goods, valued at N56,205,901,294.00 in the first quarter of this year. The command said that the tonnage of export increased from 44,502.9 metric tons to 71,014, representing an increase of 62.67 percent, when compared with the export of January to March 2021. The Comptroller added that the Free On Board (FOB) value, also increased from N31,371,825,954.00 to N56,205,901,295.00 representing an increase of 55.82 percent within the period under review. The Customs boss said the commodities exported through the command included copper ingots, stainless steel ingots, Sesame seeds, cashew nuts, cocoa beans, rubber, cocoa butter, leather, ginger, frozen shrimps among others. POLL In the area of revenue generation, Comptroller Oloyede said his command netted N135,443,223,283.31 between January and March, 2022. He said this was an improvement of N22,747,530,124.65 translating to 20.18 percent increase from the first quarter of 2021 revenue which stood at N112,695693,158.66. Comptroller Oloyede asserted that his arrival to the command about six weeks ago, signalled a new dawn in the overall performance of the command, adding that this was simply in view of the fact that he was emphatic and categorical on his vision for a renewed enthusiasm in areas of discipline, trade facilitation and revenue drive devoid of extortionist tendencies. He commended the Controller General of Customs, Col. Hameed Ibrahim Ali (Rtd.) and his management team for their relentless efforts toward strengthening the capacity of the service to perform its statutory responsibilities in line with international best practices.